# Lab Name
DOM XSS in AngularJS expression with angle brackets and double quotes HTML-encoded

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – DOM-Based XSS (AngularJS Expression Injection)

## Objective
Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability by injecting an AngularJS expression and executing JavaScript.

## Entry Point
URL query string (location.search)

## Exploitation Type
DOM-Based XSS / AngularJS Expression Injection

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and inspect the page source

2. Observe that user input is taken from:

   location.search

3. Notice that the application uses AngularJS to process and render the input

4. Verify that angle brackets (< >) and double quotes (") are HTML-encoded

5. Since AngularJS expressions are evaluated inside {{ }} blocks, direct HTML injection is not required

6. Inject a malicious AngularJS expression into the search parameter

7. Submit the payload through the URL

8. Load the page

9. Observe that AngularJS evaluates the expression and executes JavaScript

## Payload Used

{{$on.constructor('alert(1)')()}}

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript through AngularJS expression injection.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise
- Manipulation of page content

## Mitigation
- Disable evaluation of untrusted AngularJS expressions
- Upgrade vulnerable AngularJS versions
- Sanitize and validate all user-controlled input
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Avoid rendering user input inside AngularJS templates

## Learning
Even when angle brackets and quotes are encoded, AngularJS expressions may still be evaluated by the framework.
Applications using client-side template engines must treat template expressions as executable code and properly sanitize untrusted input.
